Features
--------

   Zero async: Uses reqwest::blocking, ideal for scripts and non-async applications.
   CSRF token extraction: Parses HTML login forms with configurable token field name.
   Full login flow: GET → extract token → POST with credentials, with automatic cookie management.
   Multiple output formats: Raw text, JSON, shell environment variables, or save to file.
   Customizable: Change token field name, login path, User‑Agent, redirect policy, etc.
   Robust error handling: Detailed XsrfError enum covering HTTP, I/O, parsing, and login failures.
   Well-tested: Includes unit tests, integration tests with mock servers, and a real‑world example.

  

Installation
------------

Add this to your Cargo.toml:

    [dependencies]
    libfetchxsrf = "0.1.0"    replace with actual version
    

The library depends on:

   reqwest (blocking, cookies, form)
   scraper
   serde / serdejson
   thiserror
   url
   log

If you want to run the included real‑world example, also add:

    [dev-dependencies]
    httpmock = "0.7"
    

  

Quick Start
-----------

 Fetch only a CSRF token

    use libfetchxsrf::fetchtoken;
    
    fn main() -> libfetchxsrf::Result<()> {
        let token = fetchtoken("https://target-site.com")?;
        println!("CSRF Token: {}", token);
        Ok(())
    }
    

 Login and retrieve session data

    use libfetchxsrf::{login, SessionData};
    
    fn main() -> libfetchxsrf::Result<()> {
        let session: SessionData = login(
            "https://example.com",
            "me@example.com",
            "s3cret"
        )?;
    
        println!("Cookie header: {}", session.cookiestring);
        Ok(())
    }
    

 Print session in JSON format

    use libfetchxsrf::{login, OutputFormat, SessionExt};
    
    let session = login("https://example.com", "user", "pass")?;
    session.print(OutputFormat::Json)?;
    

  

API Reference
-------------

 Top-Level Functions

 fetchtoken(baseurl: &str) -> Result<String>

Fetches the login page (/login by default), extracts the CSRF token from the hidden input named token, and returns it.

Parameters

   baseurl – Base URL of the target website (e.g., https://example.com). Trailing slash is handled automatically.

Returns  
String – The extracted CSRF token.

Example

    let token = fetchtoken("https://example.com")?;
    

  

 login(baseurl: &str, email: &str, password: &str) -> Result<SessionData>

Performs a full login:

1.  GET → fetch CSRF token
2.  POST → submit email, password, and token
3.  Collect cookies from the Set-Cookie header
4.  Return a SessionData object containing the token, parsed cookies, and the raw cookie string.

Parameters

   baseurl – Base URL of the website.
   email – Login email/username.
   password – Login password.

Returns  
SessionData struct (see below).

Example

    let session = login("https://example.com", "admin", "admin123")?;
    

  

 XsrfClient

The XsrfClient struct provides full control over the HTTP client and login process. It implements a builder pattern for customization.

 Constructor

    XsrfClient::new(baseurl: &str) -> Result<Self>
    

Creates a new client with sensible defaults:

   Token field: token
   Login path: login (relative, without leading slash)
   Redirect policy: up to 10 hops
   Timeout: 30 seconds
   User‑Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86\64) AppleWebKit/537.36

 Builder Methods

   withtokenfield(self, field: &str) -> Self  
    Sets the name of the hidden input field containing the CSRF token (e.g., csrfmiddlewaretoken).
    
   withloginpath(self, path: &str) -> Self  
    Sets the relative login path (e.g., admin/login). Do not include a leading slash.
    

 Instance Methods

    getcsrftoken(&self) -> Result<String>
    

Fetches the login page and extracts the CSRF token.

    login(&self, creds: &Credentials) -> Result<SessionData>
    

Performs the login using the given credentials and returns session data.

Example – Custom Django setup

    let client = XsrfClient::new("https://myapp.com")?
        .withtokenfield("csrfmiddlewaretoken")
        .withloginpath("accounts/login/");
    
    let creds = Credentials::new("user", "pass");
    let session = client.login(&creds)?;
    

  

 SessionData

Represents the result of a successful login.

    pub struct SessionData {
        pub csrftoken: String,
        pub cookies: Vec<CookieInfo>,
        pub cookiestring: String,
    }
    

 Methods

Method

Signature

Description

tojson

(&self) -> Result<String>

Serializes the session to a pretty-printed JSON string.

toenv

(&self) -> String

Formats the data as export shell variables (suitable for eval).

tofile

(&self, path: &str, format: &str) -> Result<()>

Saves the session to a file. format can be "json", "env", or "raw".

Examples

    let json = session.tojson()?;            // String
    let envvars = session.toenv();          // String for shell
    session.tofile("session.json", "json")?; // saved to file
    

  

 Credentials

Simple struct holding email and password.

    pub struct Credentials {
        pub email: String,
        pub password: String,
    }
    
    impl Credentials {
        pub fn new(email: impl Into<String>, password: impl Into<String>) -> Self { ... }
    }
    

  

 CookieInfo

Represents a single cookie with metadata.

    pub struct CookieInfo {
        pub name: String,
        pub value: String,
        pub domain: String,
        pub path: String,
        pub secure: bool,
        pub httponly: bool,
    }
    

Note: httponly is always set to false because the client cannot reliably determine this attribute from a Set-Cookie header via the cookie jar.

  

 OutputFormat

Enumerates the possible output modes.

    pub enum OutputFormat {
        Raw,               // human-readable token + cookie string
        Json,              // pretty JSON of SessionData
        Env,               // shell export statements
        File(String),      // save to the specified path, format inferred from extension
    }
    

  

 SessionExt Trait

Implemented for SessionData, it provides a single method:

    fn print(&self, format: OutputFormat) -> Result<()>
    

Prints the session according to the chosen format.

Example

    session.print(OutputFormat::Env);   // prints export lines
    session.print(OutputFormat::File("cookies.json".tostring())); // writes to file
    

  

 Error Types

All fallible functions return Result<T> (alias for std::result::Result<T, XsrfError>).

    pub enum XsrfError {
        Request(reqwest::Error),
        UrlParse(url::ParseError),
        TokenNotFound { field: String },
        LoginFailed { status: reqwest::StatusCode },
        Io(std::io::Error),
        Serialization(serdejson::Error),
        InvalidBody,
    }
    

Variant

Description

Request

Wraps an underlying reqwest error (connection, timeout, etc.)

UrlParse

The base URL could not be parsed

TokenNotFound

No input named field was found on the login page

LoginFailed

HTTP status of the POST was a client or server error

Io

File I/O error (e.g., saving session file)

Serialization

JSON serialization failed

InvalidBody

Used when an output format string is invalid

Example

    match login(url, email, pw) {
        Ok(session) => { / ... / },
        Err(XsrfError::LoginFailed { status }) => eprintln!("HTTP {status}"),
        Err(other) => eprintln!("{other}"),
    }
    

  

Output Formats Explained
------------------------

Raw

    CSRF Token: abc123
    Cookies: laravelsession=xyz; XSRF-TOKEN=...
    

JSON

    {
      "csrftoken": "abc123",
      "cookies": [
        {
          "name": "laravelsession",
          "value": "xyz",
          "domain": "example.com",
          "path": "/",
          "secure": true,
          "httponly": false
        }
      ],
      "cookiestring": "laravelsession=xyz; XSRF-TOKEN=..."
    }
    

Env

    export CSRFTOKEN="abc123"
    export COOKIELARAVELSESSION="xyz"
    export COOKIEXSRFTOKEN="..."
    export COOKIESTRING="laravelsession=xyz; XSRF-TOKEN=..."
    

File  
The tofile method automatically selects the format based on the file extension (json, env, or raw for anything else).  
When using print(OutputFormat::File("session.json")), it infers the format from the extension and writes the file.

  

Customization
-------------

You can override almost everything by using XsrfClient directly.

 Change the token field name

    let client = XsrfClient::new(url)?
        .withtokenfield("csrfmiddlewaretoken");
    

 Change the login URL path

    let client = XsrfClient::new(url)?
        .withloginpath("user/signin");
    

 Custom User-Agent or other request properties

To do this, build the reqwest::Client yourself and pass it to XsrfClient? Currently XsrfClient::new creates its own client. If you need full control over the client, you can modify the source or wrap it – but the default should cover most needs.

  

Real-World Example
------------------

The repository includes a complete example that reads credentials from environment variables and performs a login.

File: examples/reallogin.rs

    use libfetchxsrf::{login, OutputFormat, SessionExt};
    use std::env;
    
    fn main() {
        let baseurl = env::var("BASEURL").unwraporelse(|| "https://example.com".tostring());
        let email = env::var("EMAIL").expect("EMAIL environment variable not set");
        let password = env::var("PASSWORD").expect("PASSWORD environment variable not set");
    
        println!("Attempting login to {} as {}...\n", baseurl, email);
    
        match login(&baseurl, &email, &password) {
            Ok(session) => {
                eprintln!("Login successful!\n");
                if let Err(e) = session.print(OutputFormat::Json) {
                    eprintln!("Failed to print session: {}", e);
                }
            }
            Err(err) => {
                eprintln!("Login failed: {}", err);
                std::process::exit(1);
            }
        }
    }
    

Run it:

    EMAIL="user@example.com" PASSWORD="secret" BASEURL="https://target.com" cargo run --example reallogin
    

  

Testing
-------

The project comes with three integration test files under tests/ and a unit test in parser.rs.

 Integration tests

   tokentests.rs – Tests CSRF token extraction using a mock HTTP server.
   logintests.rs – Tests the complete login flow with simulated responses.
   sessiontests.rs – Tests JSON serialisation, environment output, and file writing of SessionData.

Run all tests:

    cargo test
    

To see logs during tests (with httpmock verbose output), set RUSTLOG:

    RUSTLOG=debug cargo test -- --nocapture
    

 Unit test

    // src/parser.rs
    [test]
    fn testextracttoken() {
        let html = r"<input type="hidden" name="token" value="abc123">";
        asserteq!(extracttoken(html, "token").unwrap(), "abc123");
    }
    

  

Logging
-------

The library uses the log crate at various levels:

   debug! – Details about URLs fetched.
   warn! – Non‑success status codes on the GET request.

To enable logging, add a logger implementation such as envlogger to your binary:

    [dependencies]
    envlogger = "0.11"
    

    fn main() {
        envlogger::init();
        // ...
    }
    

Then run with RUSTLOG=libfetchxsrf=debug to see library logs.

  

